The paper deals with the structure of sets of if-then rules, which are commonly used in machine learning and data mining. The use of these rules as attribute implications in object-attribute incidence data suggests a connection to the database subfield of computer science (cs.DB). Additionally, the paper discusses a similarity-based generalization of the relational model of data, which is a topic that falls under the umbrella of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also presents a polynomial-time algorithm, which is a common topic in the algorithms and complexity subfield (cs.DS). Finally, the paper deals with the concept of minimal sets, which is a topic that falls under the information theory subfield (cs.IT), and the use of graded rules suggests a connection to the machine learning subfield (cs.LG).
